  "prompt": "What is the salary of a cosmologist?",
  "response": "The salary of a cosmologist can vary widely based on factors such as their level of education, years of experience, the country in which they work, and the type of institution or organization they are employed by (e.g., university, research institute, government agency, or private sector).\n\nIn the United States, for example:\n- Early career cosmologists with a PhD might earn salaries ranging from $50,000 to $70,000 annually.\n- Mid-career cosmologists with experience and established research credentials can earn between $70,000 to $100,000 annually.\n- Senior cosmologists, particularly those with tenure positions at universities or those holding significant research grants, can earn salaries exceeding $100,000 annually.\n\nAdditionally, cosmologists working in high-profile research institutions or private tech companies with space-focused projects may have higher earning potential compared to those working in academia.\n\nSalaries can also be influenced by additional factors such as geographical location and specific job roles within the field of cosmology.",
